In order to assess the stability and reproducibility of the prepared devices, we checked the photovoltaic performance of the fresh device at specific intervals from Days 0 (as shown in Fig. 5
                        ) up to 60 days, with measurements taken every 10 days. The J-V graphs of the ZnO-CDs co-activated devices sensitized in Allium Cepa peel and Hibiscus rosa-sinensis dye up to 60 days are shown in Fig. 5a and b respectively. From the graphs it is clear that the Jsc of the devices remains almost same with gradual decrease in Voc as the days proceed. The decrease in Voc is mainly attributed to the evaporation of the volatile electrolyte added to it. Fig. 5c shows bar graph of the efficiencies of DSSC devices using TiO2, CDs/TiO2, and ZnO-CDs photoanodes up to 60 days in intervals of 10 days. Fig. 5d gives “improvement in efficiencies” of co-activated devices which is calculated with reference to the unmodified photoanode. The percentage of retained efficiency after 60 days is also determined and is plotted. The stability of the devices confirms that the dye was efficient in absorbing light and transferring carriers even after 60 days, with minimal loss. However, a decrease in Voc was observed, which is a common occurrence due to the evaporation of the electrolyte over time. It was noted that the presence of CDs helped to reduce the electrolyte evaporation to some extent. The reduction in the electrolyte evaporation could be due to the CDs acting as a physical barrier, preventing the electrolyte from escaping. Table 2
                         displays the photovoltaic performance of the fabricated devices in comparison with the available literature reports.
